title: Aurora Pyramid Requisition
subtitle: Housing emergency
priority: 2
max-visits: 1
tags: event
new-page: true
view-if: month >= 8 and year = 2302 and third_wave_on_society = 1 and aurora_pyramid_housing_event = 0
on-arrival: aurora_pyramid_housing_event = 1

The refugee wave has outstripped every spare bunk in Mikasa.  Squatter camps spread through Aurora's public corridors while the city council argues over budgets it does not really have.  Finally someone points at the obvious landmark: the forbidden Aurora Pyramid, hollow and half-ruined since the bank vanished, yet still plumbed, still on the municipal grid, and still tall enough to swallow a small district's worth of people.

Independent contractors and long-term squatters protest that the pyramid is *their* commons now.  The Aurora district council — one of the few bodies with real local legitimacy — votes to requisition it anyway.  Engineers estimate the structure can be partitioned into several public housing sites without waiting for megacorp salvage rights to clear.

- @public_housing: Requisition the pyramid for public housing
- @defer: Stall — keep negotiating with the squatters
- @ica_lease: Lease the pyramid to the Independent Contractors Association

